The article discusses the United States' support for the Caribbean Basin Security Initiative (CBSI), which aims to improve citizen security in the Caribbean region. The partnership between the United States and Caribbean nations focuses on combating the drug trade and other transnational crimes that threaten regional security. The CBSI is part of a larger effort that includes initiatives in Mexico, Central America, and Colombia. The United States has committed $203 million in funding for the first three years of the initiative. The article highlights the areas of cooperation, including maritime and aerial security, law enforcement capacity building, border/port security and firearms interdiction, and youth development/crime prevention. The article also mentions some accomplishments of the CBSI, such as contraband interdictions, reductions in homicides, adoption of new legislation and guidelines, intelligence sharing, anti-corruption training, and youth empowerment programs.